      "side": 1,
      "message": "iter-\u003esecond will be uint64_t, but if we’re looking at a 32-bit process and the value we seek is signed, this could be a problem.\n\nConsider what happens if the “value” side of an auxv entry in a 32-bit process is -1 \u003d 0xffffffff. We’ll pick that up in Read\u003c\u003e() as unsigned 4294967295. Then, even GetValue\u003cint32_t\u003e() will decide that 4294967295 can’t fit into an int32_t (because it can’t). The -1 will be lost.\n\nIn fact, AssignIfInRange() causes this to be a problem even if we’re looking at signed values in 64-bit processes. Unsigned 16-exa won’t do when you when you really just want negative one.\n\nI think if you wrapped iter-\u003esecond in a static_cast\u003c\u003e() to force it to a type of the correct signedness, you could overcome this. \u003ctype_traits\u003e should be able to help.\n\nSince it’s tricky stuff, though, you should also see if it’s possible to test values with the high bit set.",
      "revId": "e7ae749027e6c73e4ad3257a67b2060c9651dea5",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
